charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

This page has been set up in memory of John Asquith, who fought a brave battle with pancreatic cancer. He had not been well since February 2020, initially starting with back and stomach pains. A diagnosis of secondary lung cancer was given in July during a hospital admission. And although primary pancreatic cancer was always a possibility, John was only officially diagnosed in September and sadly passed away on Saturday 14 November. 

He was a loving and caring Husband, Dad and Father-in-law, fun-loving Grandad and great friend to many. He is missed so much and will remain forever in our hearts.

During these past few months, the Macmillan nurses have been a huge source of comfort and reassurance to John and his family. Always willing to listen at the end of the phone or visit in person. Their endless patience and calm demeanour helped through the difficult days. They helped too by contacting relevant organisations to provide support both palliatively and financially, which can so often be a minefield to navigate, even more so at a time when families are emotional and focusing on their loved one.

It was John’s wish to acknowledge the Macmillan nurses for their unfailing care and support and to help them to continue in their work. Please help us to carry out his wish and donate to this fantastic cause if you are able, all donations will be greatly appreciated.

Thank you

Carol, Sara, Amanda & Lucinda xxxx

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

eventName: Jodi’s Bike Ride London to Bruges
story:
This time last year my most amazing friend Penni received the devastating news that she had breast cancer. Thankfully she had a FANTASTIC team (including a dedicated Macmillan nurse) who have now made her a CANCER SURVIVOR!

Penni has convinced me to cycle a silly distance - 178 miles/286 kms over 3 days to raise money for this great cause. London - Bruges, over BIG hills, along windy coastal roads and navigating the traffic out of London. 

I am new to the world of cycling. In fact I don’t even have a bike yet so the next few months of training through the depths of English winter are going to be tough.

We have all been touched by cancer in some way. It would be remiss of me to write about cancer without mentioning my mum who we lost a very short 17 days after diagnosis of aggressive ovarian cancer. That was in 1998. Mum, if you are watching, I’m dedicating my ride to you.

Thanks in advance

story:

Pauline, however, with the strength and determination cultivated through years as a yoga and meditation teacher, battled on with an unwavering sunny disposition. Although I cannot change what is happening to my friend, and many more of our loved ones, I can help to raise money.

story:
Life can often be very busy, and this year has been no exception with Emma and I welcoming our first child Joshua and Jordan spending all his waking time renovating a 1930’a house.
It’s important to still take time for yourself and recharge your batteries - often overlooked.

Macmillan is a great cause and we jointly wanted to use this 24 hour gaming session to reconnect as brothers but also give something back to the world.

Whilst this certainly isn’t going to change the world, it will help make someone’s life better as a result of your donation.

story: Raising money for cancer research is such a brilliant cause, especially since the focus of the last year or so has been on Covid-19, it is easy to forget that cancer never stopped. Back in 2017, my grandfather, Tom, passed away from pancreatic cancer. The speed at which he deteriorated was mind blowing, and with no time to even process it, my family suffered greatly at the time. He was a brilliant and kind man, and I will always look up to him. It would be an honour to raise even pennies towards cancer research, every bit helps fight this terrible disease.

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
When I was 11 my mum was diagnosed with cervical cancer, after a long four years and going into remission twice my mum lost her life. Without the support from charities like Macmillan my childhood would have been a lot worse, with my dad not being present we were in a horrible financial situation and these guys stopped us from being homeless and helped to keep food on our table.

I want to give something back and help other people who are potentially in a similar situation. Cancer sucks, so let's help the other parts of their lives be that little bit better.

story:
A sponsored 24-hour gaming live stream to raise money for Macmillan Cancer Support, because why not!

Featuring: Call of Duty: Warzone, Call of Duty: Modern Warfare, Fall Guys, and much more! 

Follow here to be notified of when I'm online >> twitch.tv/jayburginn

 Countless people suffer or experience cancer in their lives. My own family, my friends families, my neighbours; In fact, I don't think I know anyone who hasn't had to experience cancer in some way. 


 Macmillan offer the absolute best support for those who go through this journey, and provide the best care they can. 


 The longest stream I've done is 6 hours.. 24 is a big jump! Let's go!


 Any money donated via the stream donation button (Paypal) or through monthly subscriptions during the stream will all be donated to this cause, but donations will be encouraged directly to JustGiving.

*DISCLAIMER*
- Twitch take 50% of subscription income, and pay live streamers the remaining 50%. I will match the 50% I receive to make up the full 100% subscription.
- Paypal apply a service charge (%) on each donation, and I will donate the difference from this too to make up 100% of the donation paid to PayPal via the stream by the viewer.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. From the 2nd of December I will be running 3K a day until the 31st of December.

Heart problems is something that has hugely impacted my family in the past and caused a lot of pain. Therefore I would like to raise as ,much money as possible for more research into heart diseases so less families are impacted upon like mine has been.

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist. Please give what you can, any donations no matter how big or small are greatly appreciated.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

For the last 37 years I have lived in Harold Hill Romford and decorated my house for the festive season. This all started with a few lights and has grown over the years. I get great joy in bringing a smile to the community.  AS I am sure you will all agree this Year has been like no other.  I decided to do my lights this year to bring a little bit of joy into everyone's lives. Especially the children.

With lots of events being cancelled i wanted to still do my display. Covid19 has had a massive effect throughout the world. And many thousands of people and children have been effected.  So if my lights bring joy to just one family then this is worth all the hard work. 

Please come and have a look. I hope you enjoy your visit. If you cant come to see it please donate on this page and visit the pictures on Face book. 

I am raising money for Great Ormond Street Children's hospital. The youngest of my Grandchildren Frankie-Poppy  had Major Heart Surgery in April 2017, And is still a regular patient at the hospital.

Frankie-Poppy is doing amazingly well and has such character always smiling and being mischievous, we all absolutely adore her. The heart operation was a great success, this was all down to the care and dedication from all the doctors and staff at the hospital. Frankie-Poppy does have a few other problems which are still being treated. 

She currently has a Kidney problem and is sometimes fed by a tube in her tummy because she has an eating disorder. But her Mummy is getting there and Frankie is getting better with it every day so hopefully eventually the tube will be removed. This is an amazing Children's hospital and worthy cause for my Christmas display. Thank you all Peter.

story:
Im geeking out for GOSH and taking on a gaming challenge to raise money for the seriously ill children,  their families and the NHS staff at Great Ormond Street Hospital. 

As GOSH plays a role in the national response to the COVID-19 crisis by treating more children from hospitals across London, resources will become increasingly stretched.   

The hospital needs the support of Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity) now more than ever, so it can continue to deliver the best, life-saving care for seriously ill children. 

Your support will help keep me going when things get tough and give me the power-up I need to complete this challenge. Its quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the give now button on the right.

story: Every day brings new challenges at Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH). Every day, 618 children and young people from across the UK arrive. Every day, doctors and nurses battle the most complex illnesses, and the brightest minds come together to achieve pioneering medical breakthroughs. And every day is a chance for you to make a difference. This extraordinary hospital has always depended on charitable support to give seriously ill children the best chance to fulfil their potential. A better future for seriously ill children STARTS HERE.

story:
Edgworth 2020 Three Legged Race Donations

It is with great sadness that this year’s event will not be going ahead, however this does not stop us doing what we all do best in coming together and donating to Cancer Research. 

COVID-19 has slowed us all down, but not Cancer... Clinical trials are being postponed and fundraising has fallen, so research had to put on hold. But this research saves lives!

1 in 2 people will get cancer in their lifetime, which is why Cancer Research are absolutely determined to continue life-saving research. This is research that will make treatments kinder, less disruptive and ultimately, will save lives.

Cancer Research are expecting to see a £160 million drop in fundraising income between now and March 2021. Put into context, £160 million is what they would spend on clinical trials over the next 10 years. A drop in fundraising income of this scale would not only be felt by the current researchers, but could also impact future life-saving breakthroughs.

To save lives tomorrow, they need your help today. Please help by donating, fundraising or sharing this message. 

Together we will still beat cancer!

story:
Hello there,

Thank you ever so much for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page!

I'm Iva and I've always wanted to do skydiving, paragliding or any sort of free-flying at some point in my life. I am usually that kind of person who likes to always plan ahead and be prepared. However, this year, nothing is going to plan! 2020 was extremely difficult and unsettling for each one of us.

Therefore, without too much planning and hesitation, I decided to give something back to someone in need by fundraising for the Cancer Research UK charity, which was greatly impacted by Covid-19.

Why did I choose this charity?

In August 2019, my mum was diagnosed with breast cancer. In the last year she has gone through painful treatments, regardless of which she managed to remain both optimistic, hopeful about the future and became much stronger than before. Fortunately, she is well now and we are looking forward to a great family Christmas together.

The money you give helps to keep the lights on in research centres, keep machines running, meaning that researchers can continue trials to find new treatments for cancer patients.

This weekend, I will be paragliding in Sopot, Bulgaria - situated at the south slopes of more that 500 kilometers long mountain range and I'm not going to lie I am scared out of my wits!

Thank you very much for all of your support! (Wish me luck!)

Iva

story:
Martin’s Dad was diagnosed with advanced metastatic prostate cancer in December 2018.  

In October 2019, we ran as a family, in the “Supernova 5k” at the Olympic Park.  Completing the course, as the Thomas family team, in just over 30 minutes but most importantly raising over £1,000 (against our target of £400).

This year, with Covid restrictions in place, we can’t meet and participate in an organised run, but Supernova are running a virtual event where runners fulfil their fundraising goals locally. As there are no organised events, this will be us out running during the cold and wet winter months, so your generosity is greatly appreciate and will help motivate us!

Our aim is to raise at least £500 to help fund the great work of Cancer Research, helping to save the lives of our loved ones.  

We will be completing a timed and mapped out 5k before the end of February 2021, and will share more details of our plans and progress in the coming weeks.

Your continued support and sponsorship is really appreciated.

Cheryl, Martin, Jay and Eva-May

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page. Please see below some more information from Cancer Research UK.

Tackling all cancers
We want survival in the UK to be among the best in the world. We’re focusing our efforts in four key areas – working to help prevent cancer, diagnose it earlier, develop new treatments and optimise current treatments by personalising them and making them even more effective.

We’ll continue to support research into all types of cancer and across all age groups. And we’re keeping our focus on understanding the biology of cancer so we can use this vital knowledge to save more lives.

We’re increasing our research in key areas such as early diagnosis, and hard-to-treat cancers including lung, pancreatic, oesophageal cancers and brain tumours.

We’re developing new tests, surgery and radiotherapy techniques, and cancer drugs. We want to personalise prevention, screening and treatment and bring benefits to patients sooner.

To help accelerate progress, we’ll be investing an additional £50 million a year into new funding schemes for our researchers. These will encourage collaboration and innovation, and support research tackling some of the biggest scientific challenges in cancer research.

story:
I started my running challenge on 25 October 2020. Originally, I planned to do 500km by Xmas day but completed it within 5 weeks (which was the personal challenge within the challenge that I set myself)

Now I have decided to extend the challenge to raise money for charity. I will hopefully run another 306km by Xmas day which means 500 miles in total.

I have chosen to raise money for Cancer Research. Just over 2 years ago I lost a very special friend, who was more like family to me, to cancer. For over 6 years he fought cancer, never once did he complain and never once did he give up. He’s on my mind and in my heart every single day but even more so when I find myself running - when I’m sore, injured, tired, cold, struggling etc...when I think about the challenge Grant went through it gives me all the motivation that I could ever need to keep on running.

G, family members, another special friend of mine who fought
cancer and all of those who continue to bravely fight against it inspire me on a daily basis.

My target is to raise £500 for this amazing charity - £1 for
each mile that I run/have ran. I hope that you can help me reach this target and truly appreciate any donations that you can make.

eventName: Painting by Swaring, Auction in Aid of Cancer Research.
story:
Hey, thank you for taking the time to check out this page. It’s aim is to promote the auction of a painting I am selling to raise money for Cancer Research UK. Are you looking for a unique, handcrafted Christmas present that supports a worthy cause? If you like and want to own this painting please put your bid in a comment against the photo. The highest bid by noon on 1st January 2020 will win this beautiful, original framed painting. Or could you support the fight against cancer by donating via my justgiving page?  https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/Samantha-Waring


I am Swaring - I used to sculpt back in the day, creating copper sculptures and water features. My pieces have been displayed in the award winning Hampton Court Garden Show and both public and private gardens. When my passion for my family overcame my passion for my work I gave this up. 


Two years ago I decided to try my hand at painting, and using YouTube tutorials to learn techniques I created a majestic mural of a tree in my hallway. However after 20 or so paintings varying from appalling to downright ugly I almost gave up. Then, the unthinkable happened and in September this year I  was diagnosed with breast cancer. 


My cancer is completely treatable and I am 10 days post my second operation. No matter the Grading or Staging or type of cancer the effects are hard both physically and Mentally. So I turned back to my Paint Brushes to help quiet my mind. The picture you are bidding on was completed 5 days post my second op. It's no masterpiece but it is easy on the eye and makes me smile when I look at it. I hope it makes you smile too. https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/Samantha-Waring


Now for the cancer facts bit - 1 in 2 people will get cancer. You WILL know someone close to you over your lifetime that will have to fight cancer. A quarter of cancers in the uk are breast cancer. Men and women get breast cancer, Do you need me to go on.. You all know the stats and most of you have your own story that will be similar or worse than mine. 


Now what can you do - I am not just begging for money - Yes you can just bid for my painting, You can just Give on my just giving page. - But what else. 


I want to inspire you to follow me in helping others - Many charities have suffered this year and money is tight but we can help. Pick a charity that is close to your heart, Pick your skill, you do have one, Your time, an unwanted gift, a service, or make something.  Make your own auction and inspire others to give.  


If nothing else please share this page to help others get involved.

https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/Samantha-Waring

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I am joining a group from University of Bristol Raising and Giving in teaming up with Choose a Challenge in order to raise money for Marie Curie by cycling 280km from Greenwich Park, London to the Eiffel Tower, Paris.

Marie Curie is the UK's leading end of life charity providing support throughout the UK in all aspects of dying, death and bereavement. They strive to ensure that patients and those affected by a diagnosis can continue to live with the best quality of life, keeping their independence and dignity for as long as possible. Each year, Marie Curie provides care for over 40,000 terminally ill patients, and with your generous donations, we will be able to support them in continuing doing so.

Bristol RAG (or Raising and Giving) is the fundraising arm of Bristol Students Union. Founded over 90 years ago to make a difference in the local community, they raise tens of thousands each year for local, national and international causes.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. 

RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.

Thank you.

charity.description:
We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story: IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story: IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive.

Your support is much appreciated.

charity.description: Médecins Sans Frontières / Doctors Without Borders (MSF) is the world's leading medical humanitarian aid organisation. We work in over 70 countries - in conflict zones, natural disasters and epidemics. We are independent, neutral and impartial. We provide medical care where it's needed most.
charity.name: Medecins Sans Frontieres / Doctors Without Borders (MSF)
eventName: In memory of Dr. Ahmed  Alhabib
story:
I am creating this page to honour my nephew Ahmed Alhabib's life.  

It is two years since Ahmed left this physical world.  Ahmed passed away as he slept after his emergency shift at George Town MedStar University Hospital, Paediatric Unit on the 7th of December 2018.  

Ahmed is  joy.   

He was nine years old when he was diagnosed with type one diabetes and was the one to comfort his family, seeing it as a condition to be managed.  

At the age of thirteen/fourteen he knew his calling in life, and that is to be a doctor.  The doctor title didn't matter to Ahmed what mattered is that he wanted to serve the underprivileged.  He always talked about wanting to go to countries where doctors are needed and wanted to be at service of people in need.  He undoubtedly enjoyed his work with underprivileged communities in Chicago, USA. 

 Ahmed spent the last eleven years of his young life studying and practicing medicine, and he enjoyed being at the service of his patients. 

Ahmed's message was that of humanity "Just be a good human, give out positive energy to as many people as you can even if it doesn't come back it doesn't matter.  Just keep doing good positive things for people around you especially your family and friends.  Let curiosity guide you toward finding what you want and always give people the benefit of doubt because you are not in their shoes".  

Ahmed was full of positive energy, a genuine heart and pure soul.  He can make everyone smile which was best fit for him to be a paediatrician.  He knew that kids would love him and he would be their hero every day.  Ahmed was not afraid of volunteering and treating patients in challenging neighbourhoods as he believed that helping people was always the right thing to do for a doctor. Ahmed loved being a doctor, a "paediatrician", and loved working with children and talked about his patients as "my children" with so much joy.  He was always the gentleman with the parents of his children no matter how difficult the situation.  He enjoyed finding funny cool toys for his "children".  

Ahmed will be mostly remembered for his contagious smile/laugh; his genuine empathy for others as well as his positive optimistic outlook on life.  He was always a breath of fresh air no matter how bad of a day you were having.  Ahmed's friends and colleagues would agree that he was always 100% present in the moment; fully immersed in every conversation, in every experience.  He always made whomever he was speaking with to feel as if they were the most important person in that moment.  

Ahmed was always welcoming, engaged and was fun.  With him you know he is paying attention to you and you can have a profound conversation. As some of his friends would say that he was the life of every gathering and he was always happy.  His aura, his positivity and his beautiful heart are contagious.

Ahmed loved life, people, food, nature and sports.  He always extended a hand of food to the homeless he met on his way to work or to school.  

Ahmed loved languages and was fluent in Arabic, English, Spanish and French, and tried his best to converse with his patients children and their families in their own languages. 

He enjoyed running, hiking, biking, skiing and playing football and many other sports.  He loved music and songs and dance

As his colleagues said in their dedication

"To Ahmed Alhabib who taught our hearts how to dance"

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
charity.registrationNumber: 288701 (England and Wales) and SC039479 (Scotland)
story: I am challenging myself to drink nothing but water this January. I am taking on the ultimate detox by avoiding caffeine, alcohol and all other drinks while supporting WaterAid. Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in communities across Ethiopia. Together, we will bring clean water to 50,000 people in Ethiopia and thousands more around the world, helping them change their own lives, forever. If you would like further information about the difference your gift will make and the positive impact it will have on peoples lives, please visit us at www.wateraid.org/uk
